        <h2 id="economic">Economic Terms</h2>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>1. Liquidation Preference</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> VCs get paid first (and potentially extra) when company exits</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Downside protection - if exit disappoints, at least get money back</p>

            <h4>The Mechanics:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>1X preference:</strong> Get investment back, then split rest pro-rata</li>
                <li><strong>2X or 3X preference:</strong> Get 2X or 3X investment back first (better for VCs)</li>
                <li><strong>Non-participating:</strong> Choose preference OR convert to common (not both)</li>
                <li><strong>Participating:</strong> Get preference AND pro-rata share (double-dipping!)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Founders prefer:</strong> 1X non-participating (least VC-friendly)</p>
            <p><strong>VCs prefer:</strong> Multiple X participating (most VC-friendly)</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>2. Dividends</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Regular payments to preferred stockholders (like bond interest)</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Get returns even if no exit happens soon</p>

            <h4>Types:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Cumulative:</strong> Dividends accumulate if not paid (pile up debt to VCs)</li>
                <li><strong>Non-cumulative:</strong> If not paid, they're gone</li>
                <li><strong>Typically 6-8% annual rate</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Founders prefer:</strong> No dividends at all (startups need cash for growth)</p>
            <p><strong>Reality:</strong> Most VC deals have no mandatory dividends (startups are illiquid)</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>3. Anti-Dilution Protection</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> If company raises at lower price (down round), VCs get extra shares to maintain value</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs (especially early investors)</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Protection if company's value drops</p>

            <h4>Types:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Full ratchet:</strong> Adjust as if VC paid the new lower price (very harsh on founders)</li>
                <li><strong>Weighted average:</strong> Blend of old and new price based on amounts (more fair)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>WHO bears the cost:</strong> Common stockholders (founders) get diluted extra</p>
            <p><strong>When it matters:</strong> Only in down rounds</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>4. Valuation Cap (for Convertible Notes)</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Maximum valuation at which note converts to equity</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> Early investors</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Cap their risk if company valuation skyrockets before conversion</p>

            <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Invest $100K on note with $5M cap</li>
                <li>Company raises Series A at $20M valuation</li>
                <li>Note converts at $5M cap (not $20M) → investor gets 4X more shares</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="control">Control and Governance Terms</h2>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>5. Board Composition</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Who sits on the board and makes major decisions</p>
            
            <p><strong>Common structure:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>2 seats for founders</li>
                <li>2 seats for VCs</li>
                <li>1 independent seat (mutually agreed)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>WHO wants control:</strong> Both founders and VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY VCs want board seats:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Oversight and monitoring</li>
                <li>Influence major decisions</li>
                <li>Protect their investment</li>
                <li>Remove CEO if needed</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>WHY founders want seats:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Keep operational control</li>
                <li>Make strategic decisions</li>
                <li>Avoid being fired</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>6. Protective Provisions</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> List of actions that require VC approval (veto power)</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Prevent founders from doing things that hurt VCs</p>

            <h4>Typical Protected Actions:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Issuing new stock (prevents dilution)</li>
                <li>Selling the company (VCs want say in exit)</li>
                <li>Changing stock rights (can't reduce VC privileges)</li>
                <li>Incurring debt above threshold (limits risk)</li>
                <li>Changing business model fundamentally</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>7. Drag-Along Rights</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> If majority votes to sell, minority must sell too</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs (and majority shareholders)</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Prevent one stubborn shareholder from blocking a good exit</p>

            <p><strong>Example scenario:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Acquirer wants to buy 100% of company</li>
                <li>VCs + founders agree (90% vote yes)</li>
                <li>One early employee with 2% says no</li>
                <li>Drag-along forces that 2% to sell</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Without drag-along:</strong> Deal could fall apart because acquirer wants 100%</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>8. Tag-Along Rights (Co-Sale)</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> If founders sell shares, VCs can sell too on same terms</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Prevent founders from cashing out and leaving VCs stuck</p>

            <p><strong>Example scenario:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Founder gets offer to sell 20% stake to private buyer</li>
                <li>VCs can tag along and sell their shares too</li>
                <li>Ensures everyone has same liquidity opportunities</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>9. Right of First Refusal (ROFR)</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> If shareholder wants to sell, company (or VCs) can buy first</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> Company and existing investors</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Control who becomes a shareholder</p>

            <p><strong>How it works:</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>Employee wants to sell 10,000 shares</li>
                <li>Gets outside offer for $5/share</li>
                <li>Company has 30 days to match the $5/share offer</li>
                <li>If company declines, VCs can match</li>
                <li>Only if both decline can employee sell to outsider</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <h2 id="other">Other Important Terms</h2>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>10. Vesting</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Founders earn their shares over time (typically 4 years)</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Ensure founders stay committed and don't leave early with all their equity</p>

            <h4>Standard Vesting:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>4-year vesting</strong></li>
                <li><strong>1-year cliff:</strong> Nothing vests until year 1, then 25% vests</li>
                <li><strong>Monthly after cliff:</strong> Remaining 75% vests monthly over 3 years</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Founder gets 1M shares with 4-year vesting, 1-year cliff</li>
                <li>Month 11: Quits → gets ZERO shares (before cliff)</li>
                <li>Month 13: Quits → gets 250K shares (cliff vested)</li>
                <li>Month 25: Quits → gets 500K shares (cliff + 12 more months)</li>
                <li>Year 4: Gets all 1M shares</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>11. Information Rights</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> VCs get regular financial statements and reports</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Monitor investment, no surprises</p>

            <h4>Typical Rights:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Monthly financial statements</li>
                <li>Annual audited financials</li>
                <li>Annual budget and business plan</li>
                <li>Board meeting attendance</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>12. Registration Rights</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> VCs can force company to file for IPO or include VC shares in IPO</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Ensure they can exit via IPO</p>

            <h4>Types:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Demand rights:</strong> VCs can force company to register for IPO</li>
                <li><strong>Piggyback rights:</strong> If company does IPO, VCs can include their shares</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>13. No-Shop Clause</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Founder can't negotiate with other VCs for X days</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> VCs</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Prevent being used for leverage while doing diligence</p>

            <p><strong>Typical duration:</strong> 30-60 days</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h3>14. Pay-to-Play</h3>
            <p><strong>What it is:</strong> VCs lose privileges if they don't invest in future rounds</p>
            
            <p><strong>WHO wants it:</strong> Lead investors in new rounds</p>
            <p><strong>WHY they want it:</strong> Punish VCs who don't support struggling company</p>

            <p><strong>Example:</strong> Series B investors say: "If you don't invest pro-rata in Series C, you lose your board seat and liquidation preference converts to common"</p>
        </div>

